columns.text:
The **Price per share** of the merger can be determined by multiplying the **Value of the merger** $(V_{BT})$ and the **number of shares of the merger**.

Let's recall that the value of the merger is given by the following formula:

$$
\begin{equation}
V_{BT}=V_B+\operatorname{NPV}
\end{equation}
$$

Where, 

- $V_B$ is the Market value of the bidder firm $(B)$, and;

- $\operatorname{NPV}$ is the (previously determined) **Net present Value** of the merger.

Now, let's solve the resulting equation we have in formula $(2)$ by evaluating the previous results of $\operatorname{NPV}$ and $V_B$:

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{BT}&=V_B+\operatorname{NPV}\\[10pt]
&=\$233,200\hspace{5pt}+\hspace{5pt}\$5,700\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\$238,900}
\end{align*}
$$

Now, as in this case we are in presence of a **Cash acquisition** the number of shares of the merger firms is the same as the number of shares that the bidder firm had!

So we can determine the **Price per share** by dividing $V_{BT}$ by the **Shares outstanding** of firm $B$:

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Price per share }_{ BT}&=\frac{V_{BT}}{\text{Shares outstanding }_{B}}\\[10pt]
&=\frac{\$238,900}{5,300}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\$45,0755}
\end{align*}
$$

So, ***<span style="color: #4257B2"> the price per share of the merged firm assuming a cash acquisition is about $\bold{\$45,08}$***</span>.

Let's recall that the **Merger premium** is the amount paid above the **stand-alone value** of the target firm:

$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Merger Premium}=\text{Value of firm $T$ to firm $B$}-\text{Market value of $B$}
\end{equation}
$$

So let's take formula $(3)$ and evaluate the previous results to find the **Merger Premium** of firms $B$ and $T$:

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Merger Premium}&=\text{Value of firm $T$ to firm $B$}-\text{Market value of $B$}\\[10pt]
&=\$22,800-\$19,200\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\$3,600}
\end{align*}
$$

***<span style="color: #4257B2"> The Merger Premium assuming a cash acquisition is $\bold{\$3,600}$***</span>.

let's start by recalling that, according to formula $(1)$ in part **a.**, the **Net Present Value** of the merger can be determined by the following formula: 


$$
\mathrm{NPV }_{BT}=V_T+\Delta V-\text { Cost }_T
$$

Where
$$
\begin{align*}
V_T&=1,200\times\$16=\$19,200\\[10pt]
\Delta V&=\$9,300\\[10pt]
\text{Cost }_{T}&=\text{New shares}\times\text{Price per share}_{BT} &=600\times\$44,3559\\
&&=\$26,613,54\hspace{17pt}
\end{align*}
$$

So the **Net Present Value** is calculated as follows:

$$
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{NPV }_{BT}&=V_T+\Delta V-\text { Cost }_T\\[10pt]
&=\$19,200+\$9,300-\$26,613,54\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,886.46}
\end{align*}
$$
